DEMO SCRIPT — Traffic Inspection & Mitigation System
=====================================================
Audience: Professor (non-technical)
Duration: ~10–15 minutes


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
BEFORE THE DEMO
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1. Start the system (do this a few minutes before she arrives):

   docker-compose up --build -d

2. Open the dashboard in a browser:

   http://localhost:8080

3. Wait until the top status bar shows:
   - IDMS     → healthy  (green dot)
   - Load Balancer → healthy  (green dot)
   - Servers online → 4 / 4

   If any are red, wait 10–15 seconds and refresh. Docker is still starting up.

4. Make sure all counters read 0. If not, click
   "Reset — Unblock All Demo IPs" to clear leftover state.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
OPENING EXPLANATION (say this before touching anything)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

"This is a load balancer — it sits in front of four servers and
 distributes incoming requests across them so no single server
 gets overwhelmed.

 The problem is that not all traffic is legitimate. Attackers can
 send fake API keys, inject malicious code into requests, or just
 flood the system with thousands of requests per second to bring
 it down.

 What I've built is an IDMS — an Intrusion Detection and
 Mitigation System — that sits in front of the load balancer and
 inspects every single request before it reaches a server.

 It works in three layers. I'll demonstrate each one."


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PHASE 1 — RULE ENGINE  (purple badge in the dashboard)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

What it is:
  A set of hard rules that run on every request in microseconds.
  No learning needed — it either matches a pattern or it doesn't.

--- Demo 1a: Wrong API Key ---

Say:
  "Every request must include a valid API key. Watch what happens
   when someone sends the wrong one."

Action: Click  [Wrong API Key]

Watch the events table:
  - A new row appears immediately
  - Result column: red "Blocked" pill
  - Detection column: purple P1 badge + "Wrong API Key"
  - What happened: "API key did not match — access denied"
  - Block counter: goes up by 1

Say:
  "That was caught and rejected before it even reached the load
   balancer. Zero compute wasted on the real servers."

Click [Reset] before the next demo.

--- Demo 1b: SQL Injection ---

Say:
  "A common attack is SQL injection — the attacker embeds database
   commands inside a normal-looking request, hoping the server will
   execute them. Watch what happens."

Action: Click  [SQL Injection]

Watch the events table:
  - Result column: orange "Honeypot" pill
  - Detection column: purple P1 + "SQL/NoSQL Injection"
  - What happened: "Attack pattern found in the request body —
                    sent to honeypot instead of real server"

Say:
  "Notice it wasn't just blocked — it was redirected to a honeypot.
   That's a decoy server. The attacker gets back a fake success
   response, so they think their attack worked and keep sending more.
   Meanwhile we're capturing everything they send, and the real
   servers never see a single malicious byte."

Click [Reset] before the next demo.

--- Demo 1c: Rate Flood ---

Say:
  "A denial-of-service attack just hammers the system with as many
   requests as possible to exhaust its resources. I'm going to
   send 250 requests in under a second from the same IP."

Action: Click  [Rate Flood (250 req)]

Watch the dashboard:
  - The Requests chart spikes sharply
  - Block counter climbs rapidly (will reach ~50+ blocks)
  - Events table fills with red "Blocked" rows
  - Detection column shows "Rate Flood"

Say:
  "The rule engine allows up to 200 requests per 10-second window
   per IP. Once that threshold is crossed, the IP is blocked for
   5 minutes and all further requests are rejected immediately —
   the attacker can't get anything through."

Point to Blocked IPs panel:
  "You can see the attacker's IP listed here with a countdown timer
   showing when the block expires. I can manually unblock it if
   needed, or just let the timer run."

Click [Reset].


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PHASE 2 — ANOMALY ENGINE  (green badge in the dashboard)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

What it is:
  Unlike Phase 1, this layer doesn't use fixed rules.
  It watches each IP's request timing over time, builds a baseline
  of what "normal" looks like for that IP, and flags behaviour
  that deviates significantly from that baseline.
  This catches sophisticated attacks that stay under fixed limits.

Say:
  "Phase 1 is good at catching known attack patterns. But a smart
   attacker might spread their flood across a longer time period,
   staying just under the rate limit. Phase 2 catches that.

   I need to teach the system what normal traffic from this IP
   looks like first. I'll send 60 requests at a steady pace."

--- Demo 2a: Warm Up ---

Action: Click  [1 · Warm Up Baseline]

Watch:
  - Status bar says "Building anomaly baseline — 60 requests at
    normal speed (~3 seconds)…"
  - Allow counter climbs from 0 to ~60 over ~3 seconds
  - Events table fills with green "Allowed" rows

Say:
  "The anomaly engine is recording the time gap between each request.
   After enough samples, it has a statistical model of this IP's
   normal behaviour — how frequently they send requests."

Wait until the Allow counter stops climbing (~3 seconds).

--- Demo 2b: Burst Attack ---

Say:
  "Now I'll simulate a burst attack — same IP, same request type,
   but sent 10 times faster than the established baseline."

Action: Click  [2 · Trigger Burst Attack]

Watch the events table:
  - New rows appear with green P2 badge "Burst Anomaly"
  - Result: yellow "Flagged" pill
  - What happened: "Requests arriving much faster than the learned
                    baseline for this IP"

Say:
  "The anomaly engine detected that the inter-arrival time between
   requests dropped far below the learned baseline. It doesn't need
   a rule that says '200 req/s is too many' — it just knows this
   is abnormal for this particular IP.

   These requests are flagged and forwarded with a warning tag, not
   blocked outright — because it could be a legitimate spike in
   traffic. But if this keeps happening..."

Action: Click  [2 · Trigger Burst Attack]  again (2–3 more times)

Watch:
  - Flagged counter keeps climbing
  - Eventually a red "Blocked" row appears with P3 pink badge
    "Escalation Block"
  - What happened: "Too many suspicious events — automatically
                    upgraded to a full block"

Say:
  "That's Phase 3 — the mitigation controller. After 20 flagged
   events within 2 minutes from the same IP, it automatically
   escalates from 'suspicious' to 'fully blocked'. The system
   learned on its own that this is not a normal traffic spike."

Click [Reset].


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
CLOSING
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Point to the counter cards:

  "At a glance you can always see the health of the system:
   - Green: legitimate traffic flowing through normally
   - Red: attackers being rejected
   - Orange: injections being trapped in the honeypot
   - Amber: suspicious traffic being flagged

   All of this happens before a single request touches a real server."

Point to the algorithm selector:

  "The load balancer itself supports three distribution algorithms —
   round robin, source hashing, and least loaded — which I can
   switch live from this dropdown."

Say:
  "The next phase of the project is a formal attack simulation and
   evaluation, where I measure false positive rates, detection
   latency, and throughput under each algorithm."


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
IF SOMETHING GOES WRONG
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Dashboard shows "connection error" or red status:
  → Run:  docker-compose ps
  → Any container not "Up"?  Run:  docker-compose up -d
  → Wait 15 seconds and refresh the browser

Phase 2 burst doesn't show anomaly events:
  → The 120-second anomaly window may have expired.
  → Click Reset, then Warm Up again, then Burst immediately after.

All counters already show high numbers:
  → Click Reset to clear demo IPs, but counters are totals
    since startup — that is fine, focus on new rows in the table.

Need to fully reset everything:
  → docker-compose down -v && docker-compose up -d
  → This wipes the SQLite database and all in-memory state.
